<h1>@HI{{hoshii}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> <strong>@HI{{hoshii}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{hoshii}}</strong> is an @HI{{i}}-adjective that expresses a desire for something. The experiencer is marked by @HI{{ha}}
and the object that is desired is marked by @HI{{ga}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@KJ{{car}}ga<strong>hoshii</strong>desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I want a car.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
As <strong>@HI{{hoshii}}</strong> is a strong adjective of emotion, the experiencer is usually the speaker. The experiencer can be
the listener if an interrogative form is used.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{child}}domoga<strong>hoshii</strong>desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Do you want a child?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<br/><br/>

In most cases where a third person is the experiencer, <strong>@HI{{hoshii}}</strong> 
will be used with <a href="grammar-garu.html">@HI{{garu}}</a> in the form @HI{{hoshigatteiru}}. There are exceptions where
<strong>@HI{{hoshii}}</strong> can be used with a third person:
<ol>
<li> with a past tense
<li> in indirect speech
<li> in explanatory situations
<li> in expressions ofconjecture.
</ol>
</p>

